NOTES_MALACHI = {
    1: {
        1: 'HEBREW: The term "massa" (Strong\'s H4853) means a burden or oracle, often used for weighty prophetic pronouncements (cf. Isa 13:1; Nah 1:1). "Malachi" (H4401) likely means "my messenger," which may be a title rather than a personal name, anticipating the "messenger" theme in 3:1. The phrase "by the hand of" (be-yad) is a standard formula for prophetic agency.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s declaration "I have loved Jacob" establishes the covenantal basis of the entire book. The Hebrew verb ahav (H157) here carries covenantal election overtones, not merely sentiment. The people\'s response ("How have you loved us?") reveals a crisis of faith — they cannot perceive YHWH\'s covenant faithfulness (hesed) amid their present circumstances, likely the post-exilic disillusionment of the 5th century BC.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: The contrast between Jacob and Esau reflects the sovereign election of YHWH (cf. Rom 9:13, where Paul cites this verse to illustrate divine election). "Hate" (sane, H8130) in Semitic idiom often means "to love less" or "to set aside," though it also carries the force of judicial rejection. The desolation of Edom\'s mountains is a historical reality fulfilled after the Babylonian and subsequent Nabataean pressures on Edomite territory.',
        4: 'HISTORICAL: "YHWH of hosts (tseva\'ot)" — this title (H6635) refers to YHWH as commander of heavenly and earthly armies and appears 24 times in Malachi alone, its highest concentration in any prophetic book. Edom (likely the Edomites displaced into the Negev, becoming the Idumeans) attempted to resettle but YHWH declares their rebuilding futile. The phrase "territory of wickedness" (gebul rish\'ah) assigns a spiritual identity to the land itself.',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: The father-son and master-servant metaphors establish the covenantal relational framework YHWH uses to indict the priests. The priests bear the special obligation of honoring YHWH\'s name, yet they are the primary violators. "Fear" (yir\'ah, H3374) in this context denotes reverential awe owed to a sovereign, not mere anxiety. This verse introduces the priestly controversy that dominates chapters 1-2.',
        7: 'HEBREW: "Polluted bread" (lechem megoa\'al) — the root ga\'al (H1351) means to defile or contaminate through ritual uncleanness. The "table of YHWH" is the altar of sacrifice, described here with contempt by the priests. This echoes the Mosaic legislation of Lev 22:17-25, which explicitly forbids blemished offerings. The priests have redefined acceptable worship on their own terms, a timeless corruption of liturgical practice.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s wish that someone would "shut the doors" of the temple is a startling statement — He would prefer the cessation of corrupt worship to its continuation. This anticipates prophetic critique seen in Amos 5:21-24 and Isa 1:11-15. The principle established here is that insincere or ritually defective worship is not neutral; it is an offense to YHWH. This verse carries profound implications for NT teaching on worship in spirit and truth (John 4:24).',
        11: 'TYPOLOGY: This verse is one of the most remarkable universalist prophecies in the OT, declaring that YHWH\'s name will be great "among the nations (goyim)" and that a "pure offering" will be made in every place. Early church fathers (Justin Martyr, Irenaeus) understood this as a prophecy of the Eucharist and the universal spread of the gospel. Whether fulfilled through the global church\'s worship or eschatologically, it anticipates the Gentile inclusion central to the NT (cf. Mal 1:11 with Acts 15:14-17; Rev 5:9).',
        14: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The title "Adon" (H113, my Lord/Master) used here alongside "YHWH of hosts" emphasizes YHWH\'s absolute sovereignty. The declaration "I am a great King" and "my name is feared among the nations" evokes the divine council imagery of Ps 47:2 and Ps 95:3, where YHWH is acclaimed as the great King over all elohim and all peoples. The concluding universal scope — "among the nations" — forms an inclusio with v.11 and frames all corrupt Israelite worship against the backdrop of YHWH\'s cosmic kingship.',
    },
    2: {
        2: 'HEBREW: The term "curse" here is \'arar (Strong\'s H779), distinct from the covenant curse term \'alah. The irony is sharp: the priestly blessing (Num 6:22-27) becomes the vehicle of curse when the priests themselves are faithless. THEOLOGICAL: The priest\'s vocation was to mediate blessing between YHWH and the people; their failure inverts the very purpose of their office, a pattern seen in corrupt leadership throughout the prophets.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "covenant with Levi" is not explicitly recorded as a formal covenant elsewhere in the Torah, but is alluded to in Num 25:12-13 (Phinehas) and Deut 33:8-11. This covenant encompasses both life and shalom (peace/wholeness, Strong\'s H7965), indicating total well-being as its gift. TYPOLOGY: Christ as the ultimate High Priest fulfills and surpasses the Levitical ideal described here (Heb 7:11-28).',
        7: 'HEBREW: The word for "messenger" is mal\'ak (Strong\'s H4397), the same word used for angelic messengers and the title of the book of Malachi itself ("my messenger"). THEOLOGICAL: The priest as mal\'ak establishes a mediatorial, ambassadorial role — he speaks the words of YHWH to the people. This anticipates the prophetic and priestly role of Christ, and the teaching office of the New Covenant community.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: The appeal to one Father and one Creator grounds the ethical demand in theology proper — covenant faithfulness among humans derives from the singular creative and paternal act of God. HISTORICAL: This verse has been debated as to whether "one father" refers to Abraham, Jacob, or God himself; the parallelism with "one God created us" strongly favors a theological rather than patriarchal referent.',
        12: 'HEBREW: The phrase "the one who is wakeful and the one who answers" (\'er we\'oneh) is notoriously difficult; it may be an idiom meaning "every last person," possibly referring to the one who calls and the one who responds in a legal or liturgical setting. The imprecatory form here calls down covenant sanctions upon the covenant-breaker.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH is named as a legal witness (\'ed, Strong\'s H5707) to the marriage covenant, grounding the sanctity of marriage in the divine council and covenant framework. TYPOLOGY: The marriage covenant between a man and the wife of his youth serves as an earthly image of YHWH\'s covenant bond with Israel (Hos 2; Eph 5:25-32), making marital treachery a form of covenant apostasy.',
        15: 'HEBREW: This verse is among the most textually difficult in the Hebrew Bible. The phrase rendered "a remnant of the spirit (ruach)" likely means God retained the capacity to create more, yet desired "godly offspring (zera\')" — highlighting that monogamous covenant marriage is the appointed context for raising covenant children. THEOLOGICAL: The ruach (spirit/breath, Strong\'s H7307) of God is seen as the animating principle behind the one-flesh union, connecting creation theology to marriage ethics.',
        16: 'HEBREW: The verb shelach ("to send away/divorce") is used in the context of legal dismissal of a wife; YHWH\'s statement "I hate divorce" (Hebrew: ki-sane\' shelach) is a direct and unambiguous moral declaration. The MT reads "he hates" (third person) in some manuscripts, creating a textual variant, but the first-person reading ("I hate") is contextually and canonically preferred. THEOLOGICAL: This is the strongest direct statement against divorce in the OT, grounding the prohibition not in social stability alone but in the character of YHWH himself.',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: The closing accusation — that Israel has morally inverted reality by calling evil good and questioning divine justice — anticipates the Day of YHWH theme developed in chapter 3. TYPOLOGY: The question "Where is the God of justice?" sets up the answer of Mal 3:1, the coming of the messenger and then YHWH himself to his temple, fulfilled in the ministry of John the Baptist and Jesus Christ (Matt 11:10; Mark 1:2).',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'TYPOLOGY: "My messenger" (Heb. mal\'aki, H4397) echoes the book\'s title and is explicitly identified as Elijah in 4:5, fulfilled in John the Baptist (Matt 11:10; Mark 1:2; Luke 7:27). "The Lord (ha-adon) whom you are seeking" is a distinct figure from the messenger — the Messiah himself — whose sudden arrival at the temple evokes the Shekinah glory returning (Ezek 43:4). "The messenger of the covenant" carries covenantal overtones linking Sinai to the new covenant inaugurated by Jesus (Heb 8:6-13). HEBREW: The definite article on "adon" (ha-adon) is emphatic, indicating "the Lord" as a specific, expected figure, distinguishable from YHWH\'s messenger who precedes him.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: The rhetorical questions "who can endure?" and "who can stand?" echo the Day of YHWH motif found in Joel 2:11 and Amos 5:18-20, signaling that the Messiah\'s coming brings both salvation and judgment. "Refiner\'s fire" points to purifying, not merely punishing, judgment — a theme developed in v. 3 (1 Pet 1:7; 1 Cor 3:13-15). HEBREW: "Borit" (H1287) refers to a plant-based alkaline soap used by fullers to cleanse cloth — a vivid image of radical moral purification.',
        3: 'TYPOLOGY: The purification of the sons of Levi anticipates the NT priesthood of all believers (1 Pet 2:5, 9; Rev 1:6), wherein Christ as High Priest purifies his people to offer spiritual sacrifices. The image of the refiner who "sits" (Heb. yashav) suggests patient, deliberate, ongoing work — not a momentary act. HISTORICAL: Ancient silver refining required the craftsman to remain seated, watching intently until he could see his reflection in the molten metal — a striking portrait of Christ\'s sanctifying scrutiny.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH lists covenant violations in descending social order — sorcerers, adulterers, false swearers, oppressors of the vulnerable — reflecting the Torah\'s ethical demands (Exod 22:21-24; Deut 24:14-15). The phrase "do not fear me" (yare\') identifies the root cause of all the listed sins: the absence of the fear of YHWH. DIVINE_COUNCIL: YHWH\'s declaration "I will draw near for judgment" positions him as the Divine Judge presiding over covenantal legal proceedings, a courtroom scene common in the prophets (Isa 1:18; Mic 6:1-2).',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s immutability (Heb. lo shaniti, "I have not changed") is the basis of Israel\'s preservation despite persistent covenant unfaithfulness. This verse is a foundational proof text for divine immutability (Num 23:19; Jas 1:17). The mercy implied — that Israel\'s existence depends not on their faithfulness but on YHWH\'s unchanging nature — is a profound expression of hesed (H2617). HEBREW: "Consumed" (kalah, H3615) carries the sense of being utterly destroyed, finished — the same root used of Israel\'s near-obliteration in other prophetic warnings.',
        8: 'HEBREW: "Rob" (qaba, H6906) is a rare and forceful term, occurring only here and in Prov 22:23. It implies seizing or defrauding by deceit or force — a shocking accusation directed at the covenant people toward their God. "Ma\'aser" (H4643) is the tithe, one-tenth of produce and livestock required by Torah (Lev 27:30-32; Num 18:21-29). "Terumah" (H8641) refers to the contribution or heave-offering, a portion lifted up and set apart for priestly use.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is the only verse in the Hebrew Bible where YHWH explicitly invites his people to "test" (bachan, H974) him — normally a prohibited act (Deut 6:16; Matt 4:7). This is not a loophole for presumption but a covenantal promise: faithful obedience to the tithe will be met with overflowing blessing. "Windows of heaven" (arubot hashamayim) echoes the Flood narrative (Gen 7:11) but now inverted — instead of judgment, abundance pours forth. HISTORICAL: The "storehouse" (otzar) was a physical treasury chamber in the Jerusalem temple complex where tithes were deposited (Neh 13:12-13).',
        16: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "book of remembrance" (sepher zikkaron, H2146) is a heavenly ledger of the faithful, a concept rooted in ancient ANE royal practice where kings maintained rolls of loyal subjects (Esth 6:1; Ps 139:16; Dan 12:1; Rev 20:12). The verb "feared" (yare\', H3372) frames covenantal loyalty as reverent awe — the antithesis of the arrogance described in vv. 13-15. This communal conversation of the faithful during apostasy prefigures the remnant theology central to Paul\'s argument in Rom 11:1-5. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The heavenly record being written "before him" (lephanav) implies a celestial court context, where YHWH presides as King over an assembled council that witnesses and documents the deeds of the faithful.',
        17: 'HEBREW: "Segullah" (H5459) is a covenant term of intimate personal ownership — used of Israel as YHWH\'s "treasured possession" in Exod 19:5, Deut 7:6, and 14:2. In ancient Near Eastern usage, segullah referred to a king\'s private treasury of jewels or prized items set apart from state property. TYPOLOGY: The father-son imagery anticipates the eschatological adoption motif of the NT, wherein believers are confirmed as sons through the Spirit (Rom 8:14-17; Gal 4:5-7), and the "day I am preparing" looks forward to the Parousia (1 Thess 4:17; Matt 25:34).',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "Burning like an oven" (tannur) is a kiln or smelting furnace, evoking total consumption. The phrase "neither root nor branch" is merism — indicating complete annihilation of lineage and legacy, a covenantal curse. THEOLOGICAL: "YHWH of hosts" (YHWH Tseva\'ot) appears here for the final time in the OT, framing the eschatological judgment as a cosmic military-executive act of the divine king. This day anticipates the NT "Day of the Lord" (2 Thess 1:7-9; Rev 19:11-15).',
        2: 'TYPOLOGY: "Sun of righteousness (tsedaqah) with healing in its wings" is messianic — the "wings" recall the fringes (tzitzit) of the garment, evoking the healing woman who touched the hem of Jesus\'s garment (Matt 9:20-22; Luke 8:44). Early church fathers (Origen, Justin Martyr) read "sun of righteousness" as a direct title for the Messiah. HEBREW: "Tsedaqah" (H6666) carries covenantal fidelity and righteous vindication, not merely moral rectitude. "Calves from the stall" pictures exuberant release from confinement into freedom — a picture of resurrection joy.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: This command to "remember the Torah of Moses" functions as a canonical hinge, sealing the entire Mosaic covenant tradition before the prophetic bridge to the new era. HISTORICAL: "Horeb" is the Deuteronomic name for Sinai, reflecting the northern/Levitical tradition. The pairing of "statutes" (chuqqim) and "rules" (mishpatim) is the standard covenantal legal formula appearing throughout Deuteronomy, signaling that Malachi\'s audience is being held accountable to the full Mosaic legal corpus.',
        5: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus explicitly identifies John the Baptist as the fulfillment of this promise (Matt 11:14; 17:10-13; Mark 9:11-13; Luke 1:17). John came "in the spirit and power of Elijah" (Luke 1:17), not as a literal reincarnation. DIVINE_COUNCIL: "The great and awesome day of YHWH" (yom YHWH) is eschatological language rooted in prophetic tradition (Joel 2:31; Amos 5:18; Zeph 1:14), describing the moment when YHWH personally intervenes in history to judge both human and heavenly powers (Isa 24:21). HISTORICAL: The historical Elijah (1 Kgs 17-2 Kgs 2) was the archetype of prophetic boldness and covenantal confrontation; his non-death (2 Kgs 2:11) made him a natural candidate for eschatological return in Second Temple expectation.',
        6: 'HEBREW: "Cherem" (H2764) — the word translated "utter destruction" or "ban" — is the most severe covenantal curse in the Hebrew lexicon, denoting total devotion to destruction, as in the conquest accounts (Josh 6:17). Its appearance as the final word of the Hebrew Old Testament is theologically arresting: the entire Torah-prophetic canon closes on the threat of covenantal rupture. THEOLOGICAL: The "turning of hearts" between generations anticipates the new covenant work of the Spirit (Ezek 36:26; Jer 31:33; Luke 1:16-17). STRUCTURE: This verse is the final verse of the entire Hebrew canon (in the MT order), making the threat of "cherem" the last word before the silence between the Testaments — a silence broken only by the proclamation of John the Baptist (Mark 1:1-4).',
    },
}